pull_request.title: Kernel: Make console refreshes work again & allocate local socket descriptors more efficiently
pull_request.body:
The `add_timer_without_id()` approach introduced in c1635e7 doesn't actually work, because that function expects the deadline to be an actual timestamp rather than an interval. If it's given a timestamp that's in the past (as happened here), it'll just return without adding the timer to the queue. Further, fixing that wouldn't have made this setup work either, because it's not possible to schedule a timer while it's still active (which was the case here because the timer was being rescheduled from within itself).

To still get the benefits that that commit was trying to get, we now use a separate thread rather than a timer (and this approach actually works).

I've also included an optimization for `sys$recvmsg`, which makes WindowServer disappear from the kmalloc stack dumps when it's idle (though there's a bunch of other stuff, mainly to do with SysFS, that still makes the system quite slow when running with those enabled).

issue.title: CORS Error on User Registration: Unable to Register New Users from Frontend
issue.body:
When a user tries to register using the frontend application, the registration request fails due to a CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing) error. The browser console displays an error message indicating that the backend server does not allow requests from the frontend‚Äôs origin.

### Steps to Reproduce
1. Open the registration page on the frontend.
2. Fill in all required registration fields.
3. Click the "Register" button.
4. Observe the error message in the browser console.

### Expected Behavior
The user should be able to register successfully, and no CORS errors should appear in the console.

### Actual Behavior
The registration fails, and a CORS error is shown in the browser console.

## Proposed Solution
Update the backend server to allow requests from the frontend origin by setting the appropriate CORS headers. This will enable successful communication between the frontend and backend during user registration.
